  "hypothesis_layer": {
    "pattern_identification": "The business cycle dynamics for 2024Q1-2025Q3 are overwhelmingly dominated by the Investment Wedge, which explains 80% of output fluctuations. Its current value is significantly above its historical mean, indicating substantial impediments to capital accumulation. The Government Wedge contributes moderately (17% of output explained) and is currently below its mean. Efficiency and Labor Wedges play a negligible role in explaining output fluctuations during this period.",
    "candidate_mechanisms": [
      {
        "wedge": "Investment Wedge",
        "mechanism": "Financial Frictions",
        "citations": [
          "Bernanke, Gertler, Gilchrist (1999)",
          "Kiyotaki & Moore (1997)"
        ],
        "reasoning": "The exceptionally high f-stat (0.80) and the positive deviation from the mean (0.87 standard deviations) for the Investment Wedge strongly suggest that frictions in financial markets are making it more costly or difficult for firms to finance new investment projects. This effectively raises the user cost of capital, dampening capital accumulation and aggregate output. Tighter credit conditions, increased risk premiums, or reduced credit supply would manifest as a higher investment wedge."
      },
      {
        "wedge": "Government Wedge",
        "mechanism": "Fiscal Policy Stance",
        "citations": [
          "Barro (1990)",
          "Ramey (2011)"
        ],
        "reasoning": "The Government Wedge's moderate f-stat (0.17) and its current position below its mean (-0.61 standard deviations) indicate that government-related factors are contributing to business cycle movements. A negative deviation could signify a less expansionary fiscal policy, such as lower government spending or effective tax rates, or a reduction in government-induced distortions, potentially affecting aggregate demand and resource allocation."
      }
    ],
